  "prompt": "What is the yield/kiloton of antimatter bomb?",
  "response": "The yield of an antimatter bomb can be theoretically calculated based on the principle of mass-energy equivalence, as described by Einstein's famous equation \\( E = mc^2 \\). Here's a step-by-step breakdown:\n\n1. **Mass-Energy Conversion Efficiency**: Matter-antimatter annihilation converts 100% of the mass into energy, making it the most efficient energy source known.\n\n2. **Energy Calculation**: For a given mass of antimatter (and an equal mass of matter to annihilate it), the total energy \\( E \\) released is:\n   \\[\n   E = 2m c^2\n   \\]\n   where \\( m \\) is the mass of antimatter and \\( c \\) is the speed of light (\\( c \\approx 3 \\times 10^8 \\, \\text{m/s} \\)).\n\n3. **Kiloton Equivalent**: 1 kiloton of TNT (kt) is equivalent to \\( 4.184 \\times 10^{12} \\) joules of energy.\n\n4. **Example Calculation**:\n   - For 1 gram of antimatter (and 1 gram of matter):\n   \\[\n   E = 2 \\times (1 \\times 10^{-3} \\, \\text{kg}) \\times (3 \\times 10^8 \\, \\text{m/s})^2 = 1.8 \\times 10^{14} \\, \\text{J}\n   \\]\n   - Convert this energy into kilotons of TNT:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Yield (kt)} = \\frac{1.8 \\times 10^{14} \\, \\text{J}}{4.184 \\times 10^{12} \\, \\text{J/kt}} \\approx 43 \\, \\text{kt}\n   \\]\n\n5. **Yield per Kiloton of Antimatter**: If you have 1 kiloton (1000 metric tons) of antimatter:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Yield (kt)} = 43 \\, \\text{kt} \\times 10^6 = 43,000,000 \\, \\text{kt}\n   \\]\n\n### Summary:\n- **1 gram of antimatter** yields approximately **43 kilotons** of energy.\n- **1 kiloton (1000 metric tons) of antimatter** yields approximately **43 million kilotons** of energy.\n\nThese values are theoretical and assume perfect annihilation efficiency. Practical challenges (e.g., containment, antimatter production) make such yields currently unattainable.",
